,"type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Graystock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Graystock","meanings":["English: locative name, from Greystoke (Cumb), recorded as  <i>Graystock</i> in 1291."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":4,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":35,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":60,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor Greystoke was born about 1255, in Litcham, Norfolk, England as the daughter of Sir Thomas Greystoke. She had at least 2 sons with Sir Robert le Strange. She died after 1326, in Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1255–Aft 1326":"umbes 1255–pärast 1326","1255–1326":"1255–1326","1256–1314":"1256–1314","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1289–1346":"1289–1346","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","24 June 1314":"24. juuni 1314","Aft 1326":"pärast 1326","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1259":"1259","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","1289":"1289","1256":"1256","1255":"1255","about 1255":"umbes 1255","about 1289":"umbes 1289","1317":"1317","Bannockburn, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Bannockburn, Stirlingshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Litcham, Norfolk, England":"Litcham, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1255–Aft 1326":"noin 1255–1326 jälkeen","1255–1326":"1255–1326","1256–1314":"1256–1314","1285–Male":"1285–Kuollut","1289–1346":"1289–1346","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","24 June 1314":"24. kesäkuuta 1314","Aft 1326":"1326 jälkeen","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1259":"1259","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","1289":"1289","